      "systemic_insight": "The 1971 war is Indira Gandhi's zenith and India's strategic peak for a generation. The military operation was textbook in planning (Manekshaw's insistence on waiting until October-November for weather and training — despite political pressure to act in April — was decisive). The diplomatic flanking (Treaty with USSR, global refugee campaign, Indira's Washington visit) was equally skilled. The result: India creates a neighbour out of its enemy's half, strips Pakistan of parity, and establishes itself as the unquestioned South Asian hegemon. The failure to convert military victory into stable peace with Pakistan — no formal treaty, no normalised relations — leaves the subcontinent's fundamental tension unresolved."
