      "region": "India — National",
      "parallel_events": [
        { "region": "Global", "description": "1975: Vietnam War ends with fall of Saigon. US influence in Asia at its lowest. Portugal's Carnation Revolution (1974) ends European fascism. Spain transitions to democracy after Franco (1975). Worldwide, authoritarian regimes are challenged — India's Emergency bucks this global trend briefly before the 1977 election reverses it." },
        { "region": "South Asia", "description": "Bangladesh's Sheikh Mujib assassinated (August 1975) — military takes over. Pakistan under Bhutto is overthrown by Zia ul-Haq (1977). South Asia in 1975–77 is a zone of democratic collapse. India's 1977 electoral reversal — an authoritarian attempt beaten by the ballot — becomes the most studied democratic resilience case in political science." }
      ],
      "systemic_insight": "The Emergency is India's most important constitutional stress test — and the system held, but not because of institutions. The Supreme Court (ADM Jabalpur case, 1976) shamefully ruled that even the right to life can be suspended during Emergency — Justice H.R. Khanna's lone dissent is the Court's saving grace. The real guardian of democracy was the electorate: Indira's miscalculation in calling elections proved that authoritarian regimes that rely on legitimacy cannot easily cancel it. The Emergency produced the 44th Amendment (1978 — restoring judicial review, changing 'internal disturbance' to 'armed rebellion,' removing property from Fundamental Rights) proving constitutional repair is possible after democratic stress."
