      "sort_year": 1984,
      "year_or_era": "1984 CE",
      "epoch_id": "nehruvian_republic",
      "event_title": "Operation Blue Star & Anti-Sikh Pogrom — Punjab Crisis and India's Darkest Urban Violence",
      "factual_description": "June 1–10, 1984 (Operation Blue Star): Indian Army storms the Golden Temple complex in Amritsar — the holiest Sikh shrine — to flush out Jarnail Singh Bhindranwale and his armed followers (Khalistan militants who had fortified the Akal Takht). The operation is militarily successful but desecrates the sacred site — the Akal Takht (highest temporal authority in Sikhism) is severely damaged. Official death count: 83 army personnel, 493 civilians, militants killed. Actual estimates much higher. The Sikh Reference Library (irreplaceable manuscripts) is burned. On October 31, 1984: Indira Gandhi is assassinated by her two Sikh bodyguards, Satwant Singh and Beant Singh, in retaliation. The assassination triggers 3 days of anti-Sikh pogroms in Delhi and other cities — officially 2,733 killed (estimates range to 8,000+). Congress leaders (H.K.L. Bhagat, Sajjan Kumar, Jagdish Tytler) are accused of organising mobs; decades of legal proceedings follow. Rajiv Gandhi succeeds Indira. Congress wins 411 of 543 Lok Sabha seats in the sympathy wave election — the largest majority in Indian electoral history.",
