      "event_title": "State Profiles: The Northeast — Seven Sisters + Sikkim: Insurgencies, Ethnic Complexity, and India's Most Biodiverse Frontier",
      "factual_description": "The Northeast comprises Assam, Arunachal Pradesh, Manipur, Meghalaya, Mizoram, Nagaland, Tripura, and Sikkim — connected to mainland India by the Siliguri Corridor (the 'Chicken's Neck': 22km wide). ASSAM: Ahom kingdom resisted 17 Mughal invasions over 600 years; fell to British in 1826 (Treaty of Yandabo). Tea (55% of India's production), Muga silk (world's only golden silk), Asia's first oil well (Digboi, 1889). NRC process produces 19 lakh stateless people — the Bangladeshi immigration anxiety drives BJP's Himanta Biswa Sarma. ARUNACHAL PRADESH: China claims 90,000 sq km as 'South Tibet'; McMahon Line (1914) disputed. 80%+ forest cover. Tawang — birthplace of 6th Dalai Lama — is the highest geopolitical flashpoint. Hydropower potential: 50,000 MW (tiny fraction tapped). MANIPUR: Meitei valley (700 sq km) surrounded entirely by hills — geography as constitutional crisis. 2023 ethnic violence (Meitei vs Kuki-Zo) kills 200+, displaces 60,000+, creates de facto ethnic partition. MEGHALAYA: Wettest place on Earth (Mawsynram/Cherrapunji, 12,000+ mm). Matrilineal Khasi, Garo, Jaintia societies. Coal economy funds patronage politics. Living root bridges over 500 years old. MIZORAM: Mizo Accord (1986) under Rajiv Gandhi — most successful insurgency-to-democracy conversion in Indian history; studied globally. 90%+ Christian; Myanmar border makes it entry point for Chin refugees. NAGALAND: Naga National Council declared independence before India's (1946). NSCN(Im) insurgency; Framework Agreement (2015) unresolved. 'Naga political issue' (Nagalim demand) is the meta-question overriding all others. Bhut jolokia — world's hottest chili. TRIPURA: 838km Bangladesh border, 84km India border. Manikya dynasty's 1,300-year lineage. Bengali refugee influx makes indigenous Tripuris a minority in their own state. CPM ruled 25 years before BJP's 2018 sweep. SIKKIM: Chogyal Buddhist kingdom merged with India in 1975 (disputed referendum). World's third-highest peak (Kangchenjunga). India's first fully organic state (2016). Smallest state, 640,000 people.",
