      "factual_description": "LAKSHADWEEP: 36 coral atolls (10 inhabited), 32 sq km land area, 4 lakh sq km EEZ — India's smallest UT but strategically enormous. 97% Muslim; matrilineal property customs; Maliku language (Maldivian-related). Arab traders dominant pre-colonial presence. Arakkal Kingdom (Kerala's only Muslim royals). India's richest tuna fishing grounds. 2021 draft regulations (Praful Patel administrator) — land sale to outsiders, alcohol, anti-social behaviour laws — triggered unprecedented protest as islanders recognised demographic-change threat. PUDUCHERRY: French India for 280 years (1674–1954, officially ceded 1962) — longest French presence in Asia. Four non-contiguous enclaves: Puducherry (Tamil Nadu coast), Karaikal (Tamil Nadu coast), Mahe (Kerala coast), Yanam (Andhra coast). Sri Aurobindo Ashram (1910) and Auroville — internationally significant intentional community founded 1968 by The Mother (Mirra Alfassa). French-quarter architecture survives; streets still in white-town and black-town grid. Cheaper alcohol and petrol than Tamil Nadu. CHANDIGARH: Built after Partition (Lahore became Pakistan's capital). Le Corbusier's master plan (1950–65) — only major city he actually built (Capitol Complex: Secretariat, High Court, Assembly). Shared capital of Punjab and Haryana — both states claim it, which is why it remains a UT. DADRA & NAGAR HAVELI and DAMAN & DIU: Portuguese territories liberated 1954 and 1961; merged into one UT 2020. Silvassa (Dadra) is a manufacturing hub (plastics, chemicals). Daman: cheaper alcohol than Gujarat (a prohibition state) — makes it a weekend liquor destination, significant excise revenue.",
